oup's leadership structure, as well as its strategies, tactics, and diverse methods of recruitment. Atwan traces the Salafi-jihadi lineage of IS, its ideological differences with al Qaeda and the deadly rivalry that has emerged between their leaders. He also shows how the group's rapid growth has been facilitated by its masterful command of social media platforms, the ";dark web,"; Hollywood blockbuster-style videos, and even jihadi computer games, producing a powerful paradox where the ambitions of the Middle Ages have reemerged in cyberspace. As Islamic State continues to dominate the world's media headlines with horrific acts of ruthless violence, Atwan considers the movement's chances of survival and expansion and offers indispensable insights on potential government responses to contain the IS threat.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aIslamic fundamentalismzMiddle East. 0aRadicalismzMiddle East. 0aSocial mediaxPolitical aspectszMiddle East. 0aSocial mediaxReligious aspects. 0aTerrorism and mass media. 0aTerrorismxComputer network resources. 0aTerrorismxReligious aspectsxIslam. 0aTerroristsxRecruiting. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / General.2bisacsh  aal qaeda.  acaliphate.  acontaining isis.  adaesh.  adark web.  aglobal jihadi movement.  ainside the islamic state.  aisil.  aisis recruitment.  aisis.  aislamic state.  ajihad.  ajihadi computer games.  amiddle eastern geopolitics.  amiddle eastern radicalism.  anew caliphate.  aorigins of daesh.  aorigins of isil.  aorigins of isis.  aorigins of the islamic state.  aradical islam.  asalafi jihadi.  asocial media recruitment for isil.  asocial media recruitment for isis.  astructure of isis.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015z9